---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import SectionHeading from "@/components/SectionHeading.astro";
---
<Layout
  title="Why Tournamental exists"
  description="Why we're building a verified, open-source tournament prediction game with a 3D watch-along, and why now."
  ogImage="/og/why.png"
>
  <article class="container-prose pt-16 pb-12">
    <SectionHeading
      eyebrow="Why Tournamental exists"
      title="Predictions are the reason people watch sport."
      lede="Every brain in the stadium is running a prediction. Every group chat is full of them. Every betting market is a billion-dollar version of them. We just want to count them properly, render them beautifully, and give the people making them the credit they deserve."
    />

    <div class="prose-vt mt-8">
      <h2>Sport is already a global prediction game</h2>
      <p>People predict every match they care about. Most of those predictions are forgotten the moment they're spoken. The sportsbook industry has built a $400 billion machine on the few that get formalised, and almost none of that value flows back to the fans, the analysts, the friends who called it three weeks ago.</p>

      <h2>The watch-along has been broken for years</h2>
      <p>Live broadcasts cost a fortune in rights, geo-block half the world, and treat the audience as passive consumers of an ad-funded feed. Live data feeds and 3D engines are now cheap and good enough that any community can render its own watch party. We ship the renderer and the protocol, anyone can plug a producer into it.</p>

      <h2>The prediction loop should be public, verifiable, and rewarded</h2>
      <p>Every prediction on Tournamental is timestamped before kickoff, signed, and verifiable for life. We call this a <strong>VStamp</strong>. Your record can be quoted, used as a credential, or fed into a higher-stakes pool, without anyone needing to trust us.</p>

      <h2>The platform should be a public good</h2>
      <p>Tournamental is open source under Apache 2.0. The docs are CC-BY 4.0. Every contributor opts in to a continuous USDC revenue share via the Drips Network. We don't believe a category-defining piece of cultural infrastructure should be owned by a single company, and we don't intend to be one.</p>

      <h2>Why now</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>3D rendering in the browser is finally good enough</strong> for a 22-player match at 60 fps on a mid-range Android.</li>
        <li><strong>Real-time data feeds</strong> from open sources (StatsBomb open data; the upcoming SimulatedSports community feeds) cover the major tournaments.</li>
        <li><strong>L2s</strong> like Arbitrum make verifiable prediction receipts cheap (cents, not dollars).</li>
        <li><strong>Distribution</strong> via Telegram, WhatsApp, and the open ATProto/ActivityPub web is no longer locked behind one app store's caprice.</li>
        <li><strong>The next FIFA World Cup is in June 2026</strong>, six weeks of global attention. We need to be ready.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How this differs from the existing bracket games</h2>
      <p>Every household-name bracket-prediction product follows the same shape: fill out one form before the tournament starts, lock everything at first kickoff, then spectate for four to six weeks. Tournamental is built the opposite way.</p>

      <div class="prose-vt-table">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th></th>
              <th>Telegraph Predictor</th>
              <th>ESPN Bracket Challenge</th>
              <th>Yahoo Tournament Pick'em</th>
              <th>Tournamental</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Can you change picks after first kickoff?</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No, locks at first tip-off</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td><strong>Yes, until that specific match kicks off</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Daily engagement during the tournament</td>
              <td>None</td>
              <td>None</td>
              <td>None</td>
              <td><strong>Daily quizzes, line bets, score-input games via Telegram bot</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>3D match watch-along</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td><strong>Yes, in-browser, no app install</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Blockchain-verified prediction receipts</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td><strong>Yes, every pick anchored to Ethereum mainnet</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Open source</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td><strong>Yes, Apache 2.0 from day one</strong></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Contributors share in platform revenue</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td><strong>Yes, paid on-chain via Drips Network</strong></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>The lock-and-spectate model made sense when a "bracket pool" lived on a single sheet of paper passed around the office. It does not make sense now. Players want to be in the game for the whole tournament, not just the five minutes it takes to fill out a form.</p>

      <p><em>(Niche newer products like 365Scores and Prodefy do offer matchday-window predictions, which is closer to our model on that one axis. None of them ship the 3D renderer, the on-chain receipts, the Telegram-bot engagement loop, or the open-source contributor split.)</em></p>

      <h2>The bet</h2>
      <p>If we get this right, every group chat, every office, every fan community has a place to save their calls and earn the credit when they're right, and the platform that hosts that activity will be entirely open, owned by the people who built it and the people who use it.</p>
      <p>That's the bet. <a href="/how-it-works" class="link">Here's how it works</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
